Goal: Create your first simple dart program.

1. Look at your project brainstorm. Find a very simple calculation, like the average height of two trees. (It doesn't matter that it's not real world useful. It's simply for learning.)

2. In VS.Code, add your git repository to the work space. (File/Add folder to workspace).

3. Create a new file. Any name without spaces is good. It should end in ".dart."

4. Use the example below to write dart code.
- You may have more than two inputs. You can see from the example how to make more.
- You may have different data types. You can explore data types here: https://dart.dev/language/built-in-types
- You can probably figure out how to change the mathematical operation.
- You can also see how text is written out.

5. Go to the command line and run the program with "dart [your file name] [your parameters]."

6. Commit and push your file to Github. (This is implied from now on and won't be repeated.)

void main(List<String> args) {
    var a = int.parse(args[0]);
    var b = int.parse(args[1]);
    var sum = a + b;

  print('The sum is $sum.');
}

Note:
- This approach of teaching has you paired with a partner. And you get to actively explore how to solve problems from day one. Your partner and the given link to the documentation should be enough to help you to figure out how to implement your own calculation.

- If you are new to command line and programming, this may require a little more help from your mentor. Also, you may still have some installation issues to work out.

Dart Pad is a convenient web page that can run arbitrary dart and flutter code. This is a useful tool to know for learning and experimenting.

1. Open dart pad: https://dartpad.dev
2. Copy and paste the program below into it.
3. Hit run.
4. Change the text and hit run again.

import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(const MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyApp({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return const MaterialApp(
      home: Scaffold(
        body: Center(
          child: Text(
            'Hello, Flutter!',
            style: TextStyle(fontSize: 32),
          ),
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

There are many choices for data stores. We are going to use the Firebase database because it is free, from Google, and part of other app tools. It's also a document-driven database, which is a little trickier to learn than relational database, yet has many performance opportunities.

1. Create a Google developer account and a Firebase project: https://console.firebase.google.com/

2. Add the Firebase database to the project.

3. Decide on a data document that you want to model based on your brainstorming doc, e.g. events, persons, trees.

4. Create a new document. You'll see the available Firebase data types in the drop down.

5. Follow these steps to install and configure Flutter Fire. (Flutter Fire integrates Firebase and Flutter.)

6. Add the following code before runApp in your Android Studio project.

7. Replace the Text on your page with the following code:

FutureBuilder(
            future: FirebaseFirestore.instance
                .collection('messages')
                .limit(1)
                .get(),
            builder: (context, snapshot) {
              if (snapshot.connectionState == ConnectionState.waiting) {
