A method declaration is similar to a a math function. It takes variables as input and has a single output.

The basic form is:
"[output data type] [method name]([input data type] [variable name] [,...) {
 [method body]
  return [return variable];
}

Example:

int sum(int a, int b) {
  int result = a + b;
  return result;
}

1. Open Dart Pad: https://dartpad.dev

2. Pick from your individual project ideas for simple methods that do some kind of calculation.

3. Create a few methods.
- You'll need a main method as an entry point.

- You'll find that there are two types of numbers in dart: integral numbers (full numbers: 1, 2, 3) and floating point numbers (numbers with a decimal: 1.23).

- To see output, you'll use print. You can show variables by putting a dollar sign in front of them $a and expressions by adding a dollar sign and parenthesis: ${a + b}. This is called string interpolation.

4. Create a new class in your Android Studio project: Create a new file and write "class UsefulFunctions {}". Copy-and-paste your methods from Dart Pad to Android Studio. (Of course, commit to Github.)

Outcome: You should declare 3-5 methods and run them.

This lesson introduces how to declare classes. Understanding object oriented design is one of the most pivotal concepts to understand in modern programming. It can take weeks to sink in at deeper and deeper levels of undestanding. Spend your time exploring the examples to stimulate your mind.

A class is essentially a collection of properties (data items) and methods/functions.

While this appears simple, it's also saying that the entire world can be distilled into attributes and behavior. Once you can look at the world and see it as attributes and behaviors, you'll unlock a big programming skill.

Here is a simple example for a class

class Tree {
  int branches = 10;

  void cutoffBranch() {
     // Correct: branches = branches - 1
     // Better: branches--;
     // Best:
     branches = max(0, branches - 1);
  }
}

You can also "nest" classes. This is called "composition.

Note: "//" slashes mark the start of comments. The compiler will ignore this. And you can leave comments for your fellow developers.

Example:
class Zoo {
  Monkey monkey = Monkey();
  Donkey donkey = Donkey();
  [...]
}

Note: Dart doesn't have or need a "new" keywork like Java and related languages.

1. Create a new package called "playground" in Android Studio.

2. Create 3-5 classes with various properties and methods.


Note:
- A method and function look the same. It is usually referred to as a function when it is by tiself. When it's part of a class, it's referred to as a method.

- Style note: When you declare properties and variables, you do not have to state the data type. You can instead simply write "var." And the IDE and compiler will figure it out.

Most people prefer this. My personal take is that it doesn't make it any easier for me to write "var" vs. "int". However, it can later be a pain to figure out what type var is if it wasn't written down.

Constructors are a special method that each class has that creates an instance of the class. If you don't provide one an empty constructor is implied. A factory method is related. It's another way of creating classes. (It's actually a step before.)

The constructor will often initialize the properties or do other initialization work.

Example:
import 'dart:math';

class Person {
   String name;
   int happiness;

   Person(String providedName) {
     name = providedName;
     happiness = Random().nextInt(10) + 1;
     // Random comes from the math package.
    }
}

Because it's so common that constructor parameters are assigned to property fields, this is a convenient shortcut:

   Person(this.name) { // <--- assigns it to the field
     happiness = Random().nextInt(10) + 1;
    }

If you need an additional constructor for a special case, factory constructors come in handy.

We could add this constructor to the above class:

   factory Person.MickeyMouse() {
      return Person("Mickey Mouse");
   }

We can call them

   var myPerson = Person("Joe");
   var yourPerson = Person.MickeyMouse();

1. Go back to your classes and add 3-5 constructors.

2. Take a look at the constructor documentation to see find other features to experiment with: https://dart.dev/language/constructors

A lot of computer science deals with lists, sets, and maps. They are ways of collecting multiple things together.

- List: An ordered list of items, e.g. runners in the order that they arrived at the finish line.

- Sets: Unordered, unique items, e.g. colors in a sock drawer.

- Map: An unordered number of name value pairs, e.g. phone number lookup; Andrea -> 310..., Bernie -> 212...

These collections can also be nested. A map of lists is common. Example, the key is the class. The value is a the list of students in that class.

Collections use generics to specify what type of items they contain. We'll learn about generics later. For now, it's simply the stuff between brackets.

Here is how to create lists, sets, and maps:

List<int> testScores = [10, 11, 9];

Set<Color> sockColors = {Colors.red, 
Colors.green, Colors.blue}

Map<String, int> scores = {
  'Alice': 10,
  'Bob': 8,
  'Charlie': 12,
};

Map<String, List<String>> favoriteFoods = {
  'Alice': ['Pizza', 'Sushi'],
  'Bob': ['Burgers', 'Salad'],
  'Charlie': ['Pasta'],
};

We need to import the material library to use Color:
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

You can ask an item in a list with the bracket operator. "print(testScores[0]);" Will print "10." (Indices are zero-based.)

Lists, sets, and maps are objects. They have methods that let you add, remove items, and do other things.

1. Go back to Android Studio and supercharge your classes with properties that are collections.

2. Take a look at the dart documentation to learn more things that you can do with dart collections: https://dart.dev/language/collections

We have been a bit hazy on what a class versus an instance is. The course is designed to introduce many concepts on the side of a lesson. That way, you've heard about concepts a few times before they are explained in depth.

A class is the blueprint. An object is a specific instance. For example, if you have a Dog class, you define the behavior of a dog once. And you can have many dogs (dog instances).

In Dart, there is a keyword called "static" that allows you to declare that a property is shared by all instances. It also declares that a method can be called without needing an instance.

For example:
class Dog {
  int barkCount = 0;
  static int barksOfAllDogs = 0;

  void bark() {
    barkCount++;
    barksOfAllDogs++;
    print('$barksofAllDogs - $barkCount');
}

void main() {
   Dog snoopy = Dog();
   Dog pluto = Dog();
   snooppy.bark();
   // Prints: 1 - 1;
   pluto.bark();
   // Prints: 2 - 1;
}

Some things are shared among all classes. A common example is to give each instance a unique ID. It would work like this:

class Dog {
   int id;
   static int lastId = 0;

   Dog() : id = ++lastId;
}

void main() {
   print(Dog().id); // prints 1
   print(Dog().id); // prints 2
}

"final" is a related keyword. It makes a field unchangeable. For example, a person's name is unlikely to change day-to-day. So, we can make it final. (Making things final can prevent bugs down the line from unintentionally changing something that shouldn't be changed.

class Person {
   final String name = "Jane Bond";
}

"const" is another important keyword. It marks a class as constant. That means that none of the properties can change. The values are known at compile time. Thus the compiler can speed up the code.

(Final can't change. Const can't change and is known at compile time.)

Example:
class Person {
  final String name;

  const Person(this.name);
}

void main() {
  const mickey = Person('Mickey Mouse');
  mickey.name = 'Minnie Mouse'; // Compile error.
}

To wrap up this lesson, we need to be clear on what a class, object/instance, and reference is. They all are distinctly different things but can appear as the same to the novice.

Recall our Dog class with the barks.

void main() {
  Dog dogA = Dog('A');
  Dog dogB = Dog('B');
  Dog dogC = dogB;

  dogA.bark(); // Prints 1 - 1
  dogB.bark(); // Prints 2 - 1
  dogC.Bark(); // prints 3 - 2
}

If you understand the above, you've got the concept.

1. Try to implement these concepts with your classes.

2. Have your mentor challenge you with exampled in Dart Pad on the understanding of them.

We are wrapping up our tour of Dart structures with class inheritance. You often have things that are very similar. For example, if we have dog, cat, and horse classes, they may share common things like they can make a sound, can be fed, and can be petted. And among dogs, we could have different dog breeds.

We model this in dart with the keyword "extends."

Example:
abstract class Animal {
  void speak();
}

abstract class Dog extends Animal {
  void bark(); // Dogs bark, so this is a dog-specific ability

  @override
  void speak() => bark(); // Speaking is barking for dogs
}

class Chihuahua extends Dog {
  @override
  void bark() => print("Yip yip!");
}

class GermanShepherd extends Dog {
  @override
  void bark() => print("Woof woof!");
}

class Cat extends Animal {
  @override
  void speak() => print("Meow!");
}

void main() {
  final animals = [
    Chihuahua(),
    GermanShepherd(),
    Cat(),
  ];

  for (var animal in animals) {
    animal.speak(); // Polymorphism: each animal speaks its own way
  }
}

Explanation:
- Animal: The "abstact" keyword says that the class cannot be instantiated.

The speak method is not provided. It's an abstract method. It must be provided in all classes that can be instantiated.

This is a mouthful: So you can't have an animal object, but you can have an animal reference to a dog object. And you can trust that for all animal references, you can call speak.

- Dog: @override marks that a method is provided for an abstract method in a parent class.

'=>' is a convenience notation for methods that are only a single method call.


