We've encountered generics when we looked at lists. Using the brackets, we could express: I want a list of Dogs.

A common problem is that a class can work on many types but a particular instance will only work with one type.

This is often connected to that we put something into the class and want the same thing out of the class. The class doesn't really care what it is, but it has to stay consistent from the callers perspective.

Example:

class Store<I> {
  I item;

  I buy(int money) {
    return I;
  }

   int sell(I item) {
      this.item = item;
      return 10;
   }
}

- On the first line, we are declaring that our class Store will handle something of type I. the caller will tell us what I is.

- The property can store an item of the type that we don't know about.

- Our methods can receive and return an item of the to be specified type.

We can call it like this:

var grocery = Store<Food>();
Food food = grocery.buy(10);


