A loop is a repeated operation. An example is to sum up all the numbers from 1 to 10. Loops often work on collections are keep executing until a condition is no longer true.

There are for types of loops:
- Indexed for loop: for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {...}
- For-in loop: for (Dog dog in dogs) {...}
- while loop
- do while loop (rarely used)

(1) An index for loop looks like this:

for ([initialization]; [ending condition]; 
[loop action] {...}

Example:
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
  print('!')';
}

We create a loop variable called "i" and initialize it with 0. Each time the loop repeats, we increase i by one. We end when i is no longer less than 5. The result is that 5 bangs will be printed out.

(2) for-in loop
List<String> flowers = ['roses', 'daises'...];
for (String flower in flowers) {
  print(flower);
}

This will print out all the flowers.

(3) while loop

while (number != 5) {
 // Ask the user for a number.
}

This will keep asking the user for a number until they correctly guess 5.

(4) do-while loop
It works like a while loop, but it's guaranteed to execute at least once.

do {
...
} while ([condition]);

1. Work with your mentor to create 5-7 examples with your individual project.

2. Take a look at the Dart documentation for loops: https://dart.dev/language/loops

Many times when we need to loop, we do operations on collections. There are a few methods that are great shortcuts for doing operations on collections. This is only a brief overview because the subject is quite broad.

For our examples, let's assume this dog class:

class Dog {
  String name;
  int weight;
  int age;

  Dog(this.name, this.weight, this.age)
}

List<Dog> dogs = [...];


(1) Filtering

var bigDogs = dogs.where((dog) => dog.weight > 50);

This makes a list of all the big dogs.

Note: "() =>" is a lambda expression. These are a bit of a mind twist. We'll learn them later. For now, use it without fully understanding it.


(2) Transforming/mapping

var names = dogs.map((dog) => dog.name).toList();

This gets a list of all the dog names.

Note: ".toList()" is needed because we are returned another collection type. So to get a list, we have to transform it into a list.

(3) Finding items

var anOldDog = dogs.firstWhere((dog) => dog.age > 10);

Finds the first old dog. (E.g. we need any old dog for a kid that came by to pet.)

(4) Summarizing/ reducing

var totalAge = dogs.fold(0, (sum, dog) => sum + dog.age);

Returns the total age of all dogs.

(5) Sorting

dogs.sort((a, b) => a.name.length.compareTo(b.name.length));

Sort the dogs with shorter names first.

A variable can have no value. We can say that it has no value by setting it to "null." Think of someone standing in line at a cafeteria. They don't have anything on their plate yet. So it is null.

Null introduces a lot of problems because the code often expects to do something with variables, e.g. call a method on it. However, when it is null, there is no object with a method to be called.

Null pointer errors used to be one of the most common bugs. Dart aims to prevent that by always declaring if something can be null. And if it can be null, the code must handle the null condition.

We can set a variable to null by adding a "?" after the type.

Example:
String? lunch;

This value is null by default.

So if we want to print out the number of characters in the lunch, this code would not compile:

print('# of chars in lunch: ${lunch.length}');

The compiler would say that lunch might be null.

There are two ways around it:

(1) Handle the condition:
if (lunch != null) {
  print('# of chars in lunch: ${lunch.length}');
} else {
  print('We haven't had lunch yet.');
}

In Dart lingo,  the if-statements "promotes" the type String? to String. Inside of the if-statement, the type is String, not String?

(2) Null-aware access operator

print('# of chars in lunch: ${lunch?.length}');

"?." checks for null. If it is null, the method won't be called and null will be returned.

It will print out "null," which may not be what we want either. At least, it doesn't break.

(3) Null-coalescent operator

print('# of chars in lunch: ${lunch?.length ?? 0}');

"??" checks for null and return what is provided. So, in this case, if lunch is null, 0 would be printed out.


