Asynchronous coding is making things execute at the same time. A common example for a Flutter app is this: Most phones render the screen with 60 FPS (Frames Per Seconds). That means, each frame has to be rendred in less then 16.67 ms. However, loading data from a server might take a few seconds. So both rendering and data loading has to happen in parallel.

Asynchronous programming can get pretty complicated. And you'll have to use it in Flutter development pretty early. So here is an introduction that gets you working rather than a deep insight.

We have the keywords "async" and "await."

By default methods, are synchronous. That means, the calling method waits until the executing method completes.

If we mark a method with "async," it becomes an asynchronous method. And the calling method returns right away.

If we want to wait for an asynchronous method to complete, we call it with the "async" keyword.

Examples:
void hello() {
  print('Hello!');
}

Future<void> ola() async {
  await Future.delayed(const Duration(seconds: 1));
  print('Ola!);
}

void main() async {
  ola();
  hello();
}

Prints "Hello!", waits for a second, prints "Ola!".


void main() async {
  await ola();
  hello();
}

Waits for a second, prints "Ola!", and then prints "Hello!".

Note: Changing a method to async and forgetting to add await to the caller can lead to tricky timing bugs.

You've probably noticed the Future<void> instead of Future. Future is a key class for concurrent programming. You'll learn a lot of good uses for it. One common need is to have two or more asynchronous calls. And you want to execute them in parallel.

Pretend that all three methods are asynchronous:

await Future.await([hello(), ola(), hey()]);


