This is going to twist your mind. If you are a hacker, you'll love the trickery that you can do with this. If you try to follow the trickery that someone else did, your head may be spinning.

We have looked at the world as class have properties and methods. However, methods/functions are first class objects themselves. We can pass around methods.

That is, I can give you a method. Your code is not aware of what that method may be, but you can call it.

Let's say we have two methods that look similar:

String translateToFrench(String english) {
  print('Voulez-vous $english');
}

String translateToSpanish(String english) {
  print('Porque $english');
}

Then we can define property that's a function pointer:

String Function(String) currentTranslator = translateToFrench;


Later, we can call

print(currentTranslator('I love NYC!'));

Depending on what currentTranslator is set to at the moment translateToFrench or translateToSpanish would get called.


How this is used:
This is often used for callbacks. Let's say that you have a dialog that asks the user something. You've created a really great dialog class that can be used in lots of cases. When you create a new dialog, you could give it a callback method. And when the dialog is done, it'll call your callback method to give you the result.


