Remember when we learned about the collection convenience methods, we encountered lambdas. Now, we are going to learn about them.

Let's say that we have code like this:

List<String> names = [...];
names.forEach(printName);

void printName(String name) {
   print('The honorable person is $name.');
}

This will iterate over all the names and print them out.

From what we learned in the last lesson, we can assume that the forEach method looks something like this:

void forEach(Function(String)) {...}

Our reference to printName here is called a tear-off:
names.forEach(printName);

A lot of times, it's a waste to declare a method with a name for this because we'll never call it by name. Thus, there are anonymous methods (aka lambdas).

names.forEach((name) => print(...));

"(name)" is a shorthand for "(String name)" becaues Dart can infer the type. And that's a shortcut for "Function(String name)".

And we've learned earlier that => is a short-hand for one instruction methods.

And that's how that short terse syntax of lambdas works.

1. Create your own method that takes a function and call it with a lambda expression.

Now that you have encountered ways to write logic, you'll realize that some properties and methods are meant to be used by callers. And some of them are only meant to be used internally. And if a caller accessed them, they could mess up your internal state. Plus, they might be confused by a lot of properties and methods that aren't useful to them.

So flutter has a way of making things private, meaning that they can only be accessed from within the same class. You can make properties and methods private by adding an underscore ("_") in front of them.

class DogTag {
  final int id;
  static int _lastId = 0;

  DogTag() : id = ++_lastId;   // assign a unique id every time
}

void main() {
  DogTag tag = DogTag();
  print('ID: ${tag.id}');
  print('Last ID: ${tag._lastId}'); // Won't compile; not allowed.
}

You can do the same with methods. Your class may have a complicated algorithm that requires multiple methods to solve sub problems. And you want to hide those methods.

Example:
class CarPaintShop {

  void paint(Car car) {
    _paintHood(car);
    _paintDoors(car);
    _paintTireRims(car);
  }
}

To spur ideas, imagine a bank  class. You might want to allow callers to depost and withdraw. However, you wouldn't want any code to change the money amount arbitrarily.

