Note: If you are coming from other language like Java, in Dart, there is only library private. Anything in the library (= package) can access it.

If you are common from Java or related languages, you are probably well familiar with getters and setters. They emerged very early. Someone realized that if a lot of code directly depends on a property, it makes changing the property very hard.

So, developers commonly create methods that get and set the value. And code calls them. That way, if there are changes down the line, the methods can change how they access the value.

This resulted in a lot of getter and setter methods that needed to be written that never ever did anything - simply because maybe, some day things could have changed.

Dart makes it simple. It says start with a property. If you ever need to inject logic, you can simply convert it to a property. Callers won't have to change.

Here are common reasons why you want to use setters/getters:

(1) Make a property readonly:
int _dollarAmount = 10;
int get dollarAmount => _dollarAmount;
// Other classes can only read dollarAmount but not set it.


(2) Compute values:
int _checkingBalance = 10;
int _savingsBalance = 20;

int get totalBalance => _checkingBalance + _totalBalance;


(3) Validate input:
int _dogAge = 10;
set dogAge(int value) {
  if (value >= 0) {
     _dogAge = value; {
  } else {
     print('Negative dog age!');
  }
}


Instructions:
