We've learned different dart language features to implement logic. On top of this, you have to use techniques and strategies. They are covered in data structure and algorithm (DSA) classes. To introduce one, here is recursive programming.

A recursive method keeps calling itself until it faces an end-condition when it returns.

A classic recursive algorithm is to reverse a string.

String reverse(String s) {
  if (s.length <= 1) return s;
  return reverse(s.substring(1)) + s[0];
}

void main() {
  print(reverse("Dog")); // goD
}

Recursion works by breaking the problem down. The method knows that the first character should be last. So it puts the first character last. And it calls itself to reverse the remaining string until the remaining string is only one character.


Finding the greatest common denominator (GCD) using the Euclidean algorithm is another great example for recursion:

int gcd(int a, int b) {
  if (b == 0) return a;     // base case
  return gcd(b, a % b);     // reduce the problem
}

void main() {
  print(gcd(42, 30)); // 6
}

Another example for recursion is to traverse a file directory and step from one directory into the next directory.

