To write effective Dart code, you not only have to know the dart language, but you have to know how to design effective code. Design patterns are strategies for using object oriented design to solve otherwise tricky problems.

A singleton is a very simple pattern. Imagine you have many pages in your app. And your pages have to share a resource. For example if we have an app to searches for events on the internet, we may have a web crawler. Different pages may want to give it work or access what it has found so far.

So we can use static to give a reference to a single object.

class Crawler {
  Crawler._(); // Private constructor so that nobody else can create an instance.
  static final Logger _instance = Crawler._();
  factory Crawler() => _instance;

  void schedule(String url) {...}
}

// Usage
final crawler = Crawler();
crawler.crawl('http://...');

Note: Why not simply make everything static? The effect is pretty similar. However, it's a lot more convenient and flexible to have an actual object instance rather than only static methods and properties.


