Note: You'll later learn about services and dependency injection, which are often better ways to solve this problem. However, the singleton pattern is so widely used that it's important to know it.

The state pattern is another good pattern to know. It's often useful when conditions get really complex and you can identify that different set of rules apply in different circumstances.

Take a look at this example. We may have a class that data storage for us. For example, it could save event pages that we crawled and which events the user wants to go to. Sometimes, we are on the subway and disconnected. So if we are in a disconnected state, the class should store the data locally.

We could create if statements that check for each different method in which state we are. However, as you see in the example, it's much more elegant to put all the online logic in one class and all the offline logic in another class.

// ---- The State abstraction ----
abstract class StorageState {
  void save(String key, String value);
}

// ---- Context: uses a state internally ----
class DataStore {
  StorageState _state;

  DataStore(this._state);

  void goOnline() {
    _state = OnlineState(this);
  }

  void goOffline() {
    _state = OfflineState(this);
  }

  void save(String key, String value) {
    _state.save(key, value);
  }

  // These helper methods are used by states:
  void _saveToServer(String key, String value) {
    // TODO: send HTTP request to server
    print('✅ Saved to server: $key=$value');
  }

  void _saveToCache(String key, String value) {
    // TODO: write to local DB or shared prefs
    print('📦 Cached locally: $key=$value');
  }
}

// ---- Concrete States ----
class OnlineState implements StorageState {
  final DataStore store;
  OnlineState(this.store);

  @override
  void save(String key, String value) {
    store._saveToServer(key, value);
  }
}

class OfflineState implements StorageState {
  final DataStore store;
  OfflineState(this.store);

  @override
  void save(String key, String value) {
    store._saveToCache(key, value);
  }
}

// ---- Demo ----
void main() {
  final store = DataStore(OfflineState(null as dynamic)); // start offline

  store.save('theme', 'dark'); // 📦 Cached locally

  store.goOnline();
  store.save('theme', 'dark'); // ✅ Saved to server
}

As you can see, there are some really smart patterns that are not immediately obvious.


