A button unlocks the user to do something. ElevatedButton is a good default widget to learn. You can associate a function with the button that gets called when the user presses it.

Example:
ElevatedButton(
            onPressed: () {
              print('One sheep counted');
            },
            child: const Text('Count a sheep'),
          )

You typically want to point onPressed to a method in your class rather than offering an anonymous inline function. It keeps the code clean.

Example:
onPressed: _countSheep;

void _countSheep() {
  // Do the sheep counting.
}

Warning! This won't work. It won't like the method but it takes the result of the method, which is not what you expect.
onPressed: _countSheep();

