You will have to create your own widgets. At a simple level, creating your own widgets helps organize your code. Rather than having one giant, many pages long statement that creates all your widgets, you'll group widgets into a custom widget.

Example: If you were to build Adobe Photoshop, you would build a lot of panels (e.g. a panel for font control, a panel for layers). Each panel would be its own widget. And then your page assembles all the panel widgets.

The need for widgets goes beyond that. You'll have to manage state. State management will cause you a lot of effort and headache in Flutter. We'll get into it in depth later.

Here is a simple way to split the world. A stateless widget always looks the same. A stateful widget changes how it looks. The user might enter text or text might come from a data source.

A preview: Flutter is very concerned about performance. If your entire screen is a stateful widget, any change requires the entire screen to re-render. However, if you create a separate stateful widget for the user badge on the page and another for the user's drawing, then changing one doesn't require the other to be re-rendered.

Here is what a stateless widget looks like:
class MyStateless extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyStateless({super.key});
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return const Text('Stateless');
  }
}

Here is what a stateful widget looks like:
class MyStateful extends StatefulWidget {
  const MyStateful({super.key});
  @override
  State<MyStateful> createState() => _MyStatefulState();
}

class _MyStatefulState extends State<MyStateful> {
  int _sheepCount = 0;
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return GestureDetector(
      onTap: () => setState(() => _sheepCount++),
      child: Text('Count: $_sheepCount'),
    );
  }
}

Notice how changing the property _sheepCount is wrapped inside of setState. That's very important. Otherwise, Flutter won't update the state correctly.

