You'll likely be able to create a crude prototype of your app once you know how to receive text input.

To receive text input, you'll need a stateful widget. What the user enters is state. You'll also need a controller that receives the text input.

We'll go into these things into more detail. For now, take a look at the example, understand what each step does, and then implement your own text input.

Example:
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

class MyInput extends StatefulWidget {
  const MyInput({super.key});
  @override
  State<MyInput> createState() => _MyInputState();
}

class _MyInputState extends State<MyInput> {
  final _controller = TextEditingController();
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Column(
      children: [
        TextField(controller: _controller),
        ElevatedButton(
          onPressed: () {
             print('Got: ${_controller.text}');
          },
          child: const Text('OK'),
        ),
      ],
    );
  }
}

Documentation: https://docs.flutter.dev/get-started/fundamentals/user-input#textfield

